<DOC><DOCNO> AP880429-0306 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-88 0308EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   04-29 0460</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0482</SECOND><DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Citizens Financial Group Inc. has agreedto be acquired for $440 million by the Royal Bank of Scotland, thesixth-largest banking group in the United Kingdom.   The acquisition will make Rhode Island the home of Royal Bank'sU.S. operations and will make the bank the flagship for futureexpansion in the Northeast, Citizens said Thursday in a statement.</TEXT><DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Enron Corp., the nation's largest natural gastransmission company, says it is considering selling its oil andgas subsidiary, one of the biggest U.S. independent oil and gasconcerns.   Chairman Kenneth L. Lay said Thursday that the sale of all orpart of Enron Oil andamp; Gas Co. ``would strengthen substantiallyEnron's financial position and provide the flexibility to pursuevery attractive opportunities we see in the energy business.''   Enron Oil andamp; Gas had reserves of 1.42 trillion cubic feet ofnatural gas and 42.3 million barrels of oil as of year-end 1987.</TEXT><DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Pennzoil Co. plans to move slowly and cautiouslyin finding ways to invest $3 billion it received from Texaco Inc.,Chairman J. Hugh Liedtke says.   ``The short of it is, we haven't fully decided on the rightcourse,'' Liedtke told shareholders Thursday at the company'sannual meeting.   Liedtke, who is giving up his position as Pennzoil's chiefexecutive officer but remaining as chairman, said the board wouldconsider a number of investments in coming months.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ford Motor Co.'s first-quarter earnings of $1.62billion set a world auto industry record for a single quarter,breaking the $1.61 billion mark set by General Motors Corp. in thefirtst quarter of 1984.   Industry analysts said after Thursday's report that they expectFord will top competitors in profitability throughout 1988.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A lawyer for RKO General Inc. has urged theFederal Communications Commission to reverse an initial decision torevoke its 14 radio and television station licenses.   Attorney Timothy Dyk told the three FCC commissioners onThursday that an administrative law judge's charge that RKO Generalhas demonstrated a pattern of dishonesty with advertisers as wellas the commission is undeserved.   Since the FCC stripped RKO of its license for WNAC-TV in Bostonin 1980, the company ``has recognized it had made a serious mistakeand has been candid with the commission,'' Dyk said.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices sagged Thursday in the slowest session of the year.The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 6.63 to 2,041.28.   Bond prices fell sharply, pushing yields on 30-year Treasurybonds to 9.10 percent from 9.02 percent.   The dollar against most other major currencies fell in lightdealings.   Futures prices declined for coffee, oil, precious metals andlivestock.</TEXT></DOC>